{{Infobox laboratory | name = The AlloSphere Research Facility | native_name = | image = Elings Hall.jpg | caption = Elings Hall which houses The AlloSphere, August 2013 | latin_name = | motto = | established = {{Start date and age|2007}} | type = | budget = | debt = | research_field = [[Technology]], [[multimedia]], [[sciences]], [[art]], [[design]] | president = | vice-president = | dean = | director = [[JoAnn Kuchera-Morin]] | head_label = | head = | faculty = | staff = | students = | alumni = | address = | city = [[Santa Barbara, California|Santa Barbara]] | state = [[California]] | province = | country = United States | coor = | zipcode = | campus = [[University of California, Santa Barbara]] | free_label = | free = | affiliations = | operating_agency = | nobel_laureates = <!--Number and/or names of Nobel laureates associated with the laboratory/institute--> | website = http://www.allosphere.ucsb.edu/ | logo = | footnotes = }}
The '''AlloSphere''' is a research facility in a theatre-like pavilion in a spherical shape, of opaque material, used to project computer-generated imagery and sounds. Included are ''GIS'', scientific, artistic, and other information.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The AlloSphere Offers an Interactive Experience of Nano-sized Worlds {{!}} NSF - National Science Foundation|url = https://www.nsf.gov/discoveries/disc_summ.jsp?cntn_id=121535|website = www.nsf.gov|accessdate = 2015-09-02}}</ref> Located at the [[University of California, Santa Barbara]] (UCSB) the AlloSphere grew out of the schools of electrical engineering and computer science, and the Media Arts & Technology program at UCSB.<ref>{{Cite web|title = JoAnn Kuchera-Morin: Stunning Data Visualization in the AlloSphere - Blog|url = http://datascience.berkeley.edu/joann-kuchera-morin-stunning-data-visualization-allosphere/|accessdate = 2015-09-02}}</ref>
The AlloSphere is housed at UCSB [[California NanoSystems Institute]]<ref>{{Cite web|title = California NanoSystems Institute {{!}} UC Santa Barbara|url = http://www.cnsi.ucsb.edu/|website = www.cnsi.ucsb.edu|accessdate = 2015-09-02}}</ref> building, "CNSI," or Elings Hall, a {{convert|62000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} facility that opened in 2007.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://engineering.ucsb.edu/pdf/facts_august2007_final.pdf |title=UC Santa Barbara Engineering Facts Brochure |date=August 2007 |accessdate=September 2, 2015 |website=UCSB College of Engineering |publisher=UCSB College of Engineering |last=Van De Werfhorst |first=Melissa |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045938/http://engineering.ucsb.edu/pdf/facts_august2007_final.pdf |archivedate=March 4, 2016 }}</ref> The AlloSphere is intended to integrate technology and media.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Marriage of Science and Art|url = http://www.ucsbalum.com/Coastlines/2011/Summer/feature_allosphere.html|website = www.ucsbalum.com|accessdate = 2015-09-02}}</ref>
The AlloSphere includes a three-story cube that has been insulated extensively with sound-absorbing material, making it one of the largest echo-less chambers in the world. Within the chamber are two hemispheres of 5 meter radii, made of perforated aluminum. These are opaque and acoustically transparent.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title = The AlloSphere at the California NanoSystems Institute, UC Santa Barbara|url = http://www.allosphere.ucsb.edu/|website = www.allosphere.ucsb.edu|accessdate = 2015-09-02}}</ref>
There are 26 video projectors, to create as much of a field of vision as possible.<ref name=":0" />
The loudspeaker real-time sound synthesis cluster (140 individual speaker elements plus sub-woofers) is suspended behind the aluminum screen resulting in 3-D audio. Computation clusters include simulation, sensor-array processing, real-time video processing for motion-capture and visual computing, render-farm/real-time ray-tracing and radiosity cluster, and content and prototyping environments.<ref name=":0" />
The AlloSphere was developed by a team of scientists, led primarily by Professor [[JoAnn Kuchera-Morin]], a professor in the field of Composition, of the Media Arts & Technology Program of UCSB.<ref name=":0" />
